'''Birchmeadow Playing Field Site''' is a {{convert|5.3|ha|adj=on}} recreational area in [[Broseley]], England, consisting of a mixture of woodland, play area, and a football pitch.<ref name="council">{{cite web |publisher=Shropshire Council |url=http://www.shropshire.gov.uk/outdoor-recreation/parks-and-countryside-sites/birchmeadow-playing-fields |title=Birchmeadow Playing Field |accessdate=17 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922115651/http://shropshire.gov.uk/outdoor-recreation/parks-and-countryside-sites/birchmeadow-playing-fields/# |archive-date=2013-09-22 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> It was also one of the first places where a wooden railway was built.<ref name="Lewis" /> The site is protected by [[Fields in Trust]] through a legal "Deed of Dedication" safeguarding the future of the space as public recreation land for future generations to enjoy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fieldsintrust.org/Birchmeadow-Park|title=Birchmeadow Park, Birchmeadow Road, Broseley, Shropshire, TF12 5AN|publisher=Fields in Trust| accessdate=23 July 2017}}</ref>
== History == An [[ironworks]] was located on the site which is now called Birchmeadow playing fields.<ref name="council" /> It was served by one of the first railways in England, built in Broseley in 1605 by Richard Wilcox and William Wells.<ref name="Lewis">{{cite book|first=M. J. T. |last=Lewis |title=Early Wooden Railways |date=1974 |pages=95–108 |publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul PLC |isbn=978-0710078186}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=R. S. |last=Smith |title=England’s First Rails: a Reconsideration |journal=Renaissance and Modern Studies |date=1960 |volume=4 |pages=125–8}}</ref> After several weeks, employees of the nearby coalmaster Lord James Clifford vandalised and damaged the railway, possibly due to a rival rift between two coalmasters.<ref>{{cite book |title=A History of Shropshire: Volume X: Wenlock, Upper Corvedale, and the Stretton Hills|date=1998 |pages=257-93 |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22876 |accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref>
== Community spaces project == In November 2009 the Birchmeadow Park Management Committee was awarded £115,000 from various grant bodies to improve the park. The grant was spent on a new woodland path, an archway, the resurfacing of the car park, and a new play facility on the site.<ref name="council" /> The park is continuing to be developed and future projects include increasing woodland management, improving the football pitches, improving the changing rooms, and enhancing the landscaping of the park.<ref name="council" />
